To control exactly how many requests are running at the same time (concurrency) rather than how fast they are going (rate), you should use a Semaphore.
While the RateLimiter we discussed previously controls requests per second, a Semaphore acts like a "Club Bouncer." It only allows a specific number of people (threads) inside the club at once. When one person leaves, the next person in line can enter.
The "Bouncer" Pattern with Virtual Threads
Here is how you can process your 180 requests (36k records / 200 per batch) while limiting the active parallel calls to exactly 10.
import com.google.common.collect.Lists;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.concurrent.Callable;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.Future;
import java.util.concurrent.Semaphore;

public class ConcurrencyControlledOrchestrator {

    private final SalesforceIntegrationService salesforceService;
    
    // The "Bouncer": Only 10 threads can pass this point at the same time.
    private final Semaphore bouncer = new Semaphore(10);

    public ConcurrencyControlledOrchestrator(SalesforceIntegrationService salesforceService) {
        this.salesforceService = salesforceService;
    }

    public void processWithConcurrencyLimit(List<SalesforceRecord> allRecords) {
        // 1. Create 180 batches
        List<List<SalesforceRecord>> batches = Lists.partition(allRecords, 200);

        // 2. Wrap each batch in a task that obeys the bouncer
        List<Callable<List<SyncResult>>> tasks = batches.stream()
            .map(batch -> (Callable<List<SyncResult>>) () -> {
                
                // --- Step A: Ask for permission to enter ---
                bouncer.acquire(); 
                
                try {
                    // --- Step B: Execute the API call ---
                    // While this is running, only 9 other threads can be here.
                    return salesforceService.pushBatchToSalesforce(batch);
                } finally {
                    // --- Step C: Leave the club so someone else can enter ---
                    // This MUST be in a finally block so we don't "leak" permits if an error occurs.
                    bouncer.release();
                }
            })
            .toList();

        // 3. Fire all 180 virtual threads
        try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
            // invokeAll starts all 180 threads, but 170 will immediately pause at bouncer.acquire()
            List<Future<List<SyncResult>>> futures = executor.invokeAll(tasks);
            
            // Gather results
            for (Future<List<SyncResult>> f : futures) {
                f.get(); // All 180 will eventually finish
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

Why this is the perfect solution for your 180 requests:
 * Efficiency: You don't have to "wait" for the whole group of 10 to finish before starting the next group. As soon as one of the 10 finishes, the 11th one starts immediately. This keeps your pipeline constantly full.
 * Virtual Thread Yielding: When a thread hits bouncer.acquire() and there are no permits left, the Virtual Thread unmounts. It doesn't block an OS thread or waste CPU cycles while waiting its turn.
 * Safety: By setting the limit to 10 or 20, you ensure you never exceed the connection pool limits of your database or the "Concurrent Request" limits of Salesforce.
Quick Comparison for your Toolkit:
 * Need to limit Requests Per Second? Use RateLimiter (Guava).
 * Need to limit Concurrent Active Connections? Use Semaphore (Standard Java).
 * Need to run things in parallel? Use Virtual Threads (Java 21).
